That would be a smart finishing layer — a short CSS block keeps everything visually coherent no matter where the widget sits.  
Here’s a lightweight stylesheet you can drop into a `<style>` tag or external `.css` file; it matches the header, main content, and footer and works on light or dark pages:

```css
/* Supportive‑Communication Toolkit — core styles */

.supportive-comm-header,
.supportive-comm-footer,
.supportive-comm-widget,
.supportive-comm-toolkit {
  font-family: system-ui, -apple-system, "Segoe UI", Roboto, sans-serif;
  line-height: 1.45;
  color: #222;
}

.supportive-comm-header {
  border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc;
  margin-bottom: 1em;
  padding-bottom: 0.6em;
}

.supportive-comm-header h2 {
  margin: 0 0 0.4em 0;
  color: #2a6ebb;
}

.supportive-comm-footer {
  border-top: 1px solid #ccc;
  margin-top: 1em;
  padding-top: 0.6em;
  font-size: 0.85em;
  color: #444;
}

.supportive-comm-widget {
  border-left: 4px solid #2a6ebb;
  background: #fafafa;
  padding: 0.8em;
  font-size: 0.95em;
  margin: 0.5em 0;
}

.supportive-comm-widget ol {
  margin: 0.3em 0 0 1.2em;
  padding: 0;
}

.supportive-comm-widget h4 {
  margin: 0 0 0.4em 0;
}

/* Optional adaptive colors for dark mode */
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  .supportive-comm-header,
  .supportive-comm-footer,
  .supportive-comm-widget {
    color: #eaeaea;
    border-color: #555;
    background: #1e1e1e;
  }
  .supportive-comm-header h2 {
    color: #8ab4f8;
  }
  .supportive-comm-widget {
    border-left-color: #8ab4f8;
  }
}
```

Drop this near the top of the page before your header/footer HTML.  
It keeps spacing and color consistent, automatically adjusts for dark mode, and doesn’t depend on any external libraries.  

